General Instructions:

  1. The clock will be set at the server. The countdown timer in the top right corner of screen will display the remaining time available for you to complete the examination. When the timer reaches zero, the examination will end by itself. You will not be required to end or submit your examination.
  2. The Question Palette displayed on the right side of screen will show the status of each question using one of the following symbols:
    1 You have not visited the question yet.
    3 You have not answered the question.
    5 You have answered the question.
    7 You have NOT answered the question, but have marked the question for review.
    9 You have answered the question, but marked it for review.
    The Marked for Review status for a question simply indicates that you would like to look at that question again. If a question is answered and Marked for Review, your answer for that question will be considered in the evaluation.
  3. You can click on the ">" arrow which appears to the left of question palette to collapse the question palette thereby maximizing the question window. To view the question palette again, you can click on "<" which appears on the right side of question window.

Navigating to a Question :

  1. To answer a question, do the following:
    1. Click on the question number in the Question Palette at the right of your screen to go to that numbered question directly. Note that using this option does NOT save your answer to the current question.
    2. To deselect your chosen answer, click on the button of the chosen option again or click on the Clear Response button
    3. To change your chosen answer, click on the button of another option
    4. To save your answer, you MUST click on the Save & Next button
    5. To mark the question for review, click on the Mark for Review & Next button.If an answer is selected for a question that is Marked for Review, that answer will be considered in the evaluation.

Answering a Question :

  1. Procedure for answering a multiple choice type question:
    1. To select your answer, click on the button of one of the options
    2. To deselect your chosen answer, click on the button of the chosen option again or click on the
    3. To change your chosen answer, click on the button of another option
    4. To save your answer, you MUST click on the Save & Next button
    5. To mark the question for review, click on the Mark for Review & Next button.If an answer is selected for a question that is Marked for Review, that answer will be considered in the evaluation.
  2. To change your answer to a question that has already been answered, first select that question for answering and then follow the procedure for answering that type of question.
  3. Note that ONLY Questions for which answers are saved or marked for review after answering will be considered for evaluation.

Navigating through sections:

  1. Sections in this question paper are displayed on the top bar of the screen. Questions in a section can be viewed by clicking on the section name. The section you are currently viewing is highlighted.
  2. After clicking the Save & Next button on the last question for a section, you will automatically be taken to the first question of the next section.
  3. You can shuffle between tests and questions anytime during the examination as per your convenience only during the time stipulated.
  4. Candidate can view the corresponding section summary as part of the legend that appears in every section above the question palette.

All the best!

    Directions: Answer the questions based on the information given below.

    The bar graph given below shows the number of Indian families and percentage of families who are Tibetans with respect to the total number of families visiting that monastery in Himachal Pradesh on Sunday.

    Note: Number of families visiting any monastery = Number of Indian families + Number of Tibetan families visiting that monastery.

    दिशानिर्देश: नीचे दी गई जानकारी के आधार पर प्रश्नों का उत्तर दें।

    नीचे दिया गया बार ग्राफ़ Sunday को Himachal Pradesh में उस मठ का दौरा करने वाले परिवारों की कुल संख्या के संबंध में भारतीय परिवारों की संख्या और Tibetan परिवारों की प्रतिशत दिखाता है।

    नोट: किसी भी मठ पर जाने वाले परिवारों की संख्या = उस मठ पर जाने वाले भारतीय परिवारों की संख्या + उस मठ पर जाने वाले Tibetan परिवारों की संख्या।

    If n = Total number of families visiting Tashi Jong monastery on Sunday – Total number of families visiting Key monastery on Sunday, then find the value of √(n + 82 – 19).

    यदि n = Sunday को Tashi Jong monastery का दौरा करने वाले परिवारों की कुल संख्या - Sunday को Key monastery पर जाने वाले परिवारों की कुल संख्या है, तो √(n + 82 – 19) का मान बताइए ?

    The bar graph given below shows the number of Indian families and percentage of families who are Tibetans with respect to the total number of families visiting that monastery in Himachal Pradesh on Sunday.

    Note: Number of families visiting any monastery = Number of Indian families + Number of Tibetan families visiting that monastery.

    दिशानिर्देश: नीचे दी गई जानकारी के आधार पर प्रश्नों का उत्तर दें।

    नीचे दिया गया बार ग्राफ़ Sunday को Himachal Pradesh में उस मठ का दौरा करने वाले परिवारों की कुल संख्या के संबंध में भारतीय परिवारों की संख्या और Tibetan परिवारों की प्रतिशत दिखाता है।

    नोट: किसी भी मठ पर जाने वाले परिवारों की संख्या = उस मठ पर जाने वाले भारतीय परिवारों की संख्या + उस मठ पर जाने वाले Tibetan परिवारों की संख्या।

    Quantity I: x = Total number of families visiting Tashi Jong Monastery on Sunday – Number of Indian families visiting Kardang Monastery on Sunday. Find the value of x.

    Quantity II: y = Number of Indian families visiting Tayul Monastery on Sunday + Number of Tibetan families visiting Key Monastery on Sunday. Find the value of y.

    मात्रा I: x = Sunday को Tashi Jong Monastery यात्रा करने वाले परिवारों की कुल संख्या - Sunday को Kardang Monastery का यात्रा करने वाले भारतीय परिवारों की संख्या, x का मान ज्ञात करें।

    मात्रा II: y = Sunday को Tayul Monastery का दौरा करने वाले भारतीय परिवारों की संख्या + Sunday को Key Monastery का दौरा करने वाले Tibetan परिवारों की संख्या। y का मान ज्ञात करें।

    Quantity-I > Quantity-II

    मात्रा-I > मात्रा-II

    Quantity-I < Quantity-II

    मात्रा-I < मात्रा-II

    Quantity-I ≤ Quantity-II

    मात्रा-I ≤ मात्रा-II

    Quantity-I = Quantity-II or No relation

    मात्रा-II और कोई सम्बन्ध नहीं

    Quantity-I ≥ Quantity-II

    मात्रा-I ≥ मात्रा-II

    In the question below there are three statements followed by two conclusions I and II. You have to take the three given statements to be true even if they seem to be at variance from commonly known facts and then decide which of the given conclusions logically follows from the three statements disregarding commonly known facts.

    Statements:

    No line is circle

    Only a few circle is square

    All square is graph

    Conclusions:

    I. All circle is graph

    II. Some square are not line

    प्रश्न में तीन कथन और उसके बाद दो निष्कर्ष I और II दिए गए हैं। आपको दिए गए तीन कथनों को सत्य मानना है, भले ही वे सामान्य रूप से ज्ञात तथ्यों से अलग दिखाई देते हों और फिर तय करें कि दिए गए निष्कर्षों में से कौन-सा निष्कर्ष सामान्य रूप से ज्ञात तथ्यों की अवहेलना करते हुए तीन कथनों का तार्किक रूप से अनुसरण करता है।

    कथन:

    कोई line circle नहीं है।

    केवल कुछ circle square है।

    सभी square graph है।

    निष्कर्ष:

    I. सभी circle graph है।

    II. कुछ square line नहीं है।

    Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows

    न तो निष्कर्ष I और न ही निष्कर्ष II अनुसरण करता है

    Only conclusion II follows

    केवल निष्कर्ष II अनुसरण करता है

    Only conclusion I follows

    केवल निष्कर्ष I अनुसरण करता है

    Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow.

    निष्कर्ष I और निष्कर्ष II दोनों अनुसरण करते हैं।

    None of the above

    उपरोक्त में से कोई नहीं

    In the question below there are three statements followed by two conclusions I and II. You have to take the three given statements to be true even if they seem to be at variance from commonly known facts and then decide which of the given conclusions logically follows from the three statements disregarding commonly known facts.

    Statements:

    Only a few Feb is Jan

    All Jan is April

    Only April is Jun

    Conclusions:

    I. All Jan being Feb is a possibility

    II. Some Jun can be Jan

    प्रश्न में तीन कथन और उसके बाद दो निष्कर्ष I और II दिए गए हैं। आपको दिए गए तीन कथनों को सत्य मानना है, भले ही वे सामान्य रूप से ज्ञात तथ्यों से अलग दिखाई देते हों और फिर तय करें कि दिए गए निष्कर्षों में से कौन-सा निष्कर्ष सामान्य रूप से ज्ञात तथ्यों की अवहेलना करते हुए तीन कथनों का तार्किक रूप से अनुसरण करता है।

    कथन:

    केवल कुछ Feb Jan है।

    सभी Jan April है।

    केवल April Jun है।

    निष्कर्ष:

    I. सभी Jan के Feb होने की संभावना है।

    II. कुछ Jun Jan हो सकते हैं।

    Only conclusion I follows

    केवल निष्कर्ष I अनुसरण करता है

    Only conclusion II follows

    केवल निष्कर्ष II अनुसरण करता है

    Neither conclusion I nor conclusion II follows

    न तो निष्कर्ष I और न ही निष्कर्ष II अनुसरण करता है

    Both conclusion I and conclusion II follow.

    निष्कर्ष I और निष्कर्ष II दोनों अनुसरण करते हैं।

    None of the above

You have to take the three given statements to be true even if they seem to be at variance from commonly known facts and then decide which of the given conclusions logically follows from the three statements disregarding commonly known facts.

    Statements:

    No table is chair

    All chair is bench

    Conclusions:

    I. Few bench is table

    II. Some chair being wood is a possibility

    प्रश्न में तीन कथन और उसके बाद दो निष्कर्ष I और II दिए गए हैं। आपको दिए गए तीन कथनों को सत्य मानना है, भले ही वे सामान्य रूप से ज्ञात तथ्यों से अलग दिखाई देते हों और फिर तय करें कि दिए गए निष्कर्षों में से कौन-सा निष्कर्ष सामान्य रूप से ज्ञात तथ्यों की अवहेलना करते हुए तीन कथनों का तार्किक रूप से अनुसरण करता है।

    कथन:

    केवल कुछ wood bench है।

    सभी chair bench है।

    निष्कर्ष:

    Directions: Answer the questions based on the information given below.

    There are two types of flats X and Y on each floor of a building.The bottommost floor is numbered as 1 and the topmost floor is numbered 5. Flat X is in west of flat Y. One person lives on each floor of each flat. There are five floors.

    Note: If a person lives n number of floors above/below another person then both must live in same type of flat until and unless stated otherwise. Also, person living on a floor of flat X is in west of person living on the same floor of flat Y.

    E lives two floors above H.F lives below G in the same type of flat but not immediately below G.B lives below F but not in the same type of flat.C lives immediately above J.A doesn’t live in flat Y.G lives in the north-west of E.F and D live on the same floor. I and A also live in the building.

    निर्देश: नीचे दी गई जानकारी के आधार पर प्रश्नों के उत्तर दें।

    In each of the following questions assuming the given statements to be true, find which of the three conclusions I, II and III given below them is/are definitely true and give your answer accordingly.

    Statements: K ≥ M, M< H, H ≤ S, M = N

    Conclusions:

    I. S > M

    II. H > N

    III. K > N

    निम्नलिखित में से प्रत्येक प्रश्न में दिए गए कथनों को सत्य मानते हुए ज्ञात करें कि नीचे दिए गए तीन निष्कर्ष I, II और III में से कौन-सा निष्कर्ष निश्चित रूप से सत्य है और तदनुसार अपना उत्तर दें।

    कथन: K ≥ M, M< H, H ≤ S, M = N

    निष्कर्ष:

    I. S > M

    II. H > N

    III. K > N

    Only conclusion I is true

    केवल निष्कर्ष I सत्य है

    Only conclusions I and II is true

    केवल निष्कर्ष I और II सत्य है

    Only conclusion III is true

    केवल निष्कर्ष III सत्य है

    Only conclusions I and III are true

    केवल निष्कर्ष I और III सत्य हैं

    Only conclusion II is true

    केवल निष्कर्ष II सत्य है

    I. R > A

He then turns left from point O and walks for 6m till point P and then turns right and walks for 4m till point Q and then turns right and walks for 9m till point R. He then turns right and walks for 4m and then turns left from point S and walks for 3m till point T.

    निर्देश: नीचे दी गई जानकारी के आधार पर प्रश्नों के उत्तर दें।

    एक व्यक्ति बिंदु M से दक्षिण दिशा में चलना शुरू करता है, 4m चलने के बाद वह बिंदु N से बाएं मुड़ता है और बिंदु O तक 3m चलता है। फिर वह बिंदु O से बाएं मुड़ता है और बिंदु P तक 6m चलता है और फिर दाएं मुड़ता है और बिंदु Q तक 4m चलता है और फिर दाएं मुड़ता है और बिंदु R तक 9m चलता है। फिर वह दाएं मुड़ता है और 4m चलता है और फिर बिंदु S से बाएं मुड़ता है और बिंदु T तक 3m चलता है।

    Point M is in which direction with respect to point S?

    बिंदु S के सन्दर्भ में बिंदु M किस दिशा में है?

    North-East

    Six functions A, B, C, D, E and F are held on 1st of different months (March, April, May, July, August and September) in the same year. These functions are held in different places among Bhopal, Pune, Jaipur, Chennai, Mumbai and Hyderabad.

    Two functions are held between F and D, which is held in a month, which has only 30 days.One function is held between C and the one held in Mumbai. E is held in Chennai but after C.

    Function in Pune is held before A.Function in Bhopal is held four months after B. The function in Mumbai is held immediately before F. Function in Hyderabad is not held in a month, which has only 30 days.

    निर्देश: नीचे दी गई जानकारी के आधार पर प्रश्नों के उत्तर दें।

    छह समारोह A, B, C, D, E और F एक ही वर्ष में अलग-अलग महीनों (मार्च, अप्रैल, मई, जुलाई, अगस्त और सितंबर) की पहली तारीख को आयोजित किए जाते हैं। ये समारोह भोपाल, पुणे, जयपुर, चेन्नई, मुंबई और हैदराबाद के बीच विभिन्न स्थानों पर आयोजित किए जाते हैं।

    F और D के बीच दो समारोह आयोजित किए जाते हैं और D को उस महीने में आयोजित किया जाता है, जिसमें केवल 30 दिन होते हैं। C और मुंबई में आयोजित एक समारोह के बीच एक समारोह आयोजित किया जाता है। E चेन्नई में आयोजित किया जाता है लेकिन C के बाद।

    पुणे में समारोह को A से पहले आयोजित किया जाता है। भोपाल में समारोह को B के चार महीने बाद आयोजित किया जाता है। मुंबई में समारोह को F से ठीक पहले आयोजित किया जाता है। हैदराबाद में समारोह उस महीने में नहीं होता है, जिसमें केवल 30 दिन होते हैं।

    D is held in which place?

    उपरोक्त में से कोई नहीं

    The question given below consists of two statements numbered I and II below them. You have to decide whether the data provided in the statements are sufficient to answer the question. Read all the statements and give answer:

    6 boxes A, B, C, D, E and F are kept one above the other. How many boxes are between B and A?

    Statement I: B is 2 boxes above E. C is 2 boxes above D. A is not above B. There are 2 boxes below E. F is not the topmost box.

    Statement II: There are 3 boxes between C and A. D is 2 boxes above A. B is above E and F. B is not the topmost box.

    इस प्रश्न में दो कथन I और II दिए गए हैं|आपको यह तय करना है कि कथन में दी गई जानकारी उत्तर देने के लिए पर्याप्त है या नहीं|

    6 boxes A, B, C, D, E और F को एक दुसरे के ऊपर रखा जाता है|B और A के बीच कितनी boxes हैं?

    कथन I: B E से 2 boxes ऊपर है|C D से 2 boxes ऊपर है|A B के ऊपर नहीं है|E के नीचे 2 boxes है|F शीर्षतम box नहीं है|

    कथन II: C और A के बीच 3 boxes है|D A से 2 boxes ऊपर है|B E और F के ऊपर है|B शीर्षतम box नहीं है|

    If the data given in statement I alone is sufficient to answer the question.

    सिर्फ कथन I में दी गयी जानकारी प्रश्न का उत्तर देने के लिए पर्याप्त है

    If the data given in statement II alone is sufficient to answer the question.

    सिर्फ कथन II में दी गयी जानकारी प्रश्न का उत्तर देने के लिए पर्याप्त है

    If the data given in either statement I or statement II alone is sufficient to answer the question.

    या तो सिर्फ कथन I या सिर्फ कथन II में दी गयी जानकारी उत्तर देने के लिए पर्याप्त है|

    If the data given in both statement I and statement II together are sufficient to answer the question.

    दोनों कथन I और II में दी गई संयुक्त जानकारी उत्तर देने के लिए पर्याप्त है|

    If the data given in both statement I and statement II together are not sufficient to answer the question.

    दोनों कथन I और II में दी गई संयुक्त जानकारी उत्तर देने के लिए पर्याप्त नहीं है|

    The question consists of two statements numbered I and II given below it. You have to decide whether the data provided in the statements are sufficient to answer the question.

    Six persons, P through U are sitting around a circular table. All of them are facing the centre. Who is sitting opposite to S?

    Statement I: P is sitting 2nd to the right of R, who is sitting 2nd to the right of Q, who is sitting adjacent to T. U is not sitting adjacent to P.

    Statement II: R is sitting opposite to T, who is sitting 2nd to the left of U.

    इस प्रश्न में दो कथन I और II दिए गए हैं|आपको यह तय करना है कि कथन में दी गई जानकारी उत्तर देने के लिए पर्याप्त है या नहीं|

    छह व्यक्ति, P से U एक वृत्ताकार टेबल पर बैठे हैं|सभी का मुख केंद्र की ओर है|S के विपरीत कौन बैठा है?

    कथन I: P R के दाएँ से दुसरे स्थान पर बैठा है और R Q के दाएँ से दुसरे स्थान पर बैठा है और Q T के बगल में बैठा है|U P के बगल में नहीं बैठा है|

    कथन II: R T के विपरीत बैठा है और T U के बाएँ से दुसरे स्थान पर बैठा है|

    The data in statement I alone are sufficient to answer the question, while the data in statement II alone are not sufficient to answer the question

    सिर्फ कथन I में दी गयी जानकारी प्रश्न का उत्तर देने के लिए पर्याप्त है, जबकि सिर्फ कथन II में दी गई जानकारी उत्तर देने के लिए पर्याप्त नहीं है|

    The data in statement II alone are sufficient to answer the question, while the data in statement I alone are not sufficient to answer the question

    सिर्फ कथन II में दी गयी जानकारी प्रश्न का उत्तर देने के लिए पर्याप्त है, जबकि सिर्फ कथन I में दी गई जानकारी उत्तर देने के लिए पर्याप्त नहीं है|

    The data either in statement I alone or in statement II alone are sufficient to answer the question

    या तो सिर्फ कथन I या सिर्फ कथन II में दी गयी जानकारी उत्तर देने के लिए पर्याप्त है|

    The data given in both statements I and II together are not sufficient to answer the question

    दोनों कथन I और II में दी गई संयुक्त जानकारी उत्तर देने के लिए पर्याप्त नहीं है|

    The data in both statements I and II together are necessary to answer the question.

    दोनों कथन I और II में दी गई संयुक्त जानकारी उत्तर देने के लिए आवश्यक है|

    Three persons are sitting between G and B. T is sitting opposite to the person, who is sitting adjacent to B. R is sitting 2nd to the right of T and neither of them are sitting at any of the extreme ends. Q is sitting immediately right of V, who is sitting opposite to G. E is sitting 2nd to the left of F. Neither E nor F is sitting adjacent to G. P is sitting opposite to C. U is not sitting opposite to B. A is not sitting at the extreme end. S is not sitting adjacent to R.

    R. Digital technologies allow us to work anytime or anywhere.

    S. However, we often find ourselves in paradoxical situations whereby we end up working everywhere or all the time.

    T. Although digital technologies blur the boundaries between work and non-work, it is essential that we somehow restore those boundaries in the context of remote working.

    Which of the following would be the FIFTH statement after rearrangement?

    Q

    R

    P

    S

    T

    Directions: Read the following passage carefully and answer the questions.

    Many of the important benefits of a plant-based diet – particularly for climate health and animals – are well known. Yet despite the science being very clear, there remains confusion about the impact on human health. We have long known for example, that a diet centred around whole plant-foods – fruits, vegetables, whole-grains, beans, nuts and seeds – significantly reduces the risk of heart disease, type 2 diabetes, obesity and certain cancers. In fact, a low fat plant-based diet is the only diet to have been shown to actually reverse established coronary artery disease. It has also been seen to reverse type 2 diabetes, enable effective and sustained weight loss without portion control or exercise, and arrest the progression of early stage prostate cancer.

    Diet choices can have a major impact on mood and mental health, and there is a very good reason for this. Diet affects the health of our gut bacteria, which produce many of the hormones active in the brain. Gut bacteria thrive on fibre, which is only found in whole plant foods. So it is no surprise to find that a plant-based diet can benefit mental health. In a study, participants who were overweight or had a history of type 2 diabetes were either prescribed a low-fat vegan diet or asked to continue their usual diet for 18 weeks. The results showed a significant improvement in mental health, wellbeing and work productivity in those on the vegan diet, as well as lower levels of depression and anxiety.

    Osteoarthritis, the painful breakdown of cartilage in the joints, appears to be an inevitable consequence of ageing. It is not reversible but it is manageable, usually with pain medication and sometimes surgery.

    So what role could a plant-based diet play here? One small study looking at the diet’s impact showed a significant improvement in self-reported pain and functioning in people with osteoarthritis. One reason for this could be the anti-inflammatory properties of the micro-nutrients present in plant foods, as inflammation is the main cause of pain in arthritis. Meat-based diets have the opposite effect and, in general, increase the level of inflammation in the body.

    Urinary tract infections (UTIs) are one of the most common causes of infection in the general population with the bacteria Escherichia coli (E coli) often being the culprit. Infection can occur because E coli from the intestine finds its way into the urinary tract. But UTIs can also be caused by E coli strains commonly found in farm animals such as chickens and pigs, so eating contaminated sources of meat can lead to infection. Given the link between E coli and UTIs, It might seem obvious that those on a plant-based diet who avoid meat might have a lower risk of infection, but whether this was the case was not known for sure until recent research came out. The analysis of several studies shows that vegetarians have a 16% lower risk of UTIs compared to non-vegetarians. This confirms previous data suggesting that meat-borne bacteria are a major contributor to the risk of UTIs. Increasingly these food borne bacteria are displaying antibiotic resistance.

    So if those following a health plant-based diet have a lower risk of ill health then surely this will save on health costs. In a large Taiwanese study, vegetarians were found to have a lower rate of outpatient visits, which translated into a 13% lower outpatient expenditure and a 15% lower total medical expenditure. So it is interesting to hypothesise the health economic impact of a plant-based diet on the UK’s cash-strapped National Health Service. In 2017, spending on healthcare in the UK totalled £197 billion – approximately £2,989 per person. If everyone in the country shifted to a vegetarian diet, this could (using the 15% reduction as a guide) reduce healthcare expenditure by £30 billion. Plant-based diets then, not only have the potential to dramatically improve human and planetary health, but could have significant benefits for the health of the economy too.

    Based on the information given in the passage, which of the following statements is TRUE?

    Diet choices do not affect the mental health of an individual.

    Plant based diets are as likely to cause inflammation in your body as meat based diets.

This confirms previous data suggesting that meat-borne bacteria are a major contributor to the risk of UTIs. Increasingly these food borne bacteria are displaying antibiotic resistance.

    So if those following a health plant-based diet have a lower risk of ill health then surely this will save on health costs. In a large Taiwanese study, vegetarians were found to have a lower rate of outpatient visits, which translated into a 13% lower outpatient expenditure and a 15% lower total medical expenditure. So it is interesting to hypothesise the health economic impact of a plant-based diet on the UK’s cash-strapped National Health Service. In 2017, spending on healthcare in the UK totalled £197 billion – approximately £2,989 per person. If everyone in the country shifted to a vegetarian diet, this could (using the 15% reduction as a guide) reduce healthcare expenditure by £30 billion. Plant-based diets then, not only have the potential to dramatically improve human and planetary health, but could have significant benefits for the health of the economy too.

    Directions: Read the following passage carefully and answer the questions.

    Many of the important benefits of a plant-based diet - particularly for climate health and animals - are well known. Yet despite the science being very clear, there remains confusion about the impact on human health. We have long known for example, that a diet centred around whole plant-foods - fruits, vegetables, whole-grains, beans, nuts and seeds - significantly reduces the risk of heart disease, type 2 diabetes, obesity and certain cancers. In fact, a low fat plant-based diet is the only diet to have been shown to actually reverse established coronary artery disease. It has also been seen to reverse type 2 diabetes, enable effective and sustained weight loss without portion control or exercise, and arrest the progression of early stage prostate cancer.

    Diet choices can have a major impact on mood and mental health, and there is a very good reason for this. Diet affects the health of our gut bacteria, which produce many of the hormones active in the brain. Gut bacteria thrive on fibre, which is only found in whole plant foods. So it is no surprise to find that a plant-based diet can benefit mental health. In a study, participants who were overweight or had a history of type 2 diabetes were either prescribed a low-fat vegan diet or asked to continue their usual diet for 18 weeks. The results showed a significant improvement in mental health, wellbeing and work productivity in those on the vegan diet, as well as lower levels of depression and anxiety.

    Osteoarthritis, the painful breakdown of cartilage in the joints, appears to be an inevitable consequence of ageing. It is not reversible but it is manageable, usually with pain medication and sometimes surgery.

    So what role could a plant-based diet play here? One small study looking at the diet's impact showed a significant improvement in self-reported pain and functioning in people with osteoarthritis. One reason for this could be the anti-inflammatory properties of the micro-nutrients present in plant foods, as inflammation is the main cause of pain in arthritis. Meat-based diets have the opposite effect and, in general, increase the level of inflammation in the body.

    Urinary tract infections (UTIs) are one of the most common causes of infection in the general population with the bacteria Escherichia coli (E coli) often being the culprit. Infection can occur because E coli from the intestine finds its way into the urinary tract. But UTIs can also be caused by E coli strains commonly found in farm animals such as chickens and pigs, so eating contaminated sources of meat can lead to infection. Given the link between E coli and UTIs, It might seem obvious that those on a plant-based diet who avoid meat might have a lower risk of infection, but whether this was the case was not known for sure until recent research came out. The analysis of several studies shows that vegetarians have a 16% lower risk of UTIs compared to non-vegetarians. This confirms previous data suggesting that meat-borne bacteria are a major contributor to the risk of UTIs. Increasingly these food borne bacteria are displaying antibiotic resistance.

    So if those following a health plant-based diet have a lower risk of ill health then surely this will save on health costs. In a large Taiwanese study, vegetarians were found to have a lower rate of outpatient visits, which translated into a 13% lower outpatient expenditure and a 15% lower total medical expenditure. So it is interesting to hypothesise the health economic impact of a plant-based diet on the UK's cash-strapped National Health Service. In 2017, spending on healthcare in the UK totalled ≤197 billion - approximately ≤2,989 per person. If everyone in the country shifted to a vegetarian diet, this could (using the 15% reduction as a guide) reduce healthcare expenditure by ≤30 billion. Plant-based diets then, not only have the potential to dramatically improve human and planetary health, but could have significant benefits for the health of the economy too.

    People should limit the consumption of dairy and meat.

    One of the leading causes of emissions is meat based diet.

    People should eat everything in moderation.

    People should switch to a plant based diet as it offers a range of benefits and also helps in tackling climate change.

    None of the above

    Directions: Read the following passage and answer the questions.

    On December 5, the world marked World Soil Day. The theme this year, “Stop Soil Erosion, Save our Future,” was chosen to raise awareness of the damage being done to soils around the world and start the process of reversing this trend.

    There is no doubt that they should. The importance of soil to human civilization cannot be overestimated – it is present in everything we touch. Healthy soil underpins agriculture, farm productivity, and national economies. It grows healthy food, reduces nutrient losses to waterways, reduces greenhouse-gas emissions, increases carbon sequestration, and strengthens biodiversity, all while enabling crops to cope with the changing climate. As such, the soil should be viewed as a natural, national, and strategic asset that must be managed wisely.

    Yet around the world, soils are being eroded, dried out, and degraded, owing to poor land use and intensive agricultural practices that deplete soil nutrients. Other factors contributing to poor soil health and erosion include deforestation, excessive use of nitrogen fertilizers, and overgrazing. Ultimately, these practices literally mine the life out of soils. It is time to reverse this damaging trend.

    One way to ensure that national governments and citizens appreciate soils and the value they hold is to put an economic price tag on them. Compelling recent evidence suggests that there are substantial profits to be made from caring about soils. Putting a price tag on the soil is the right way to encourage the necessary efforts.

    Regenerative agriculture, while encompassing many other principles, comprises sustainable farming practices such as reduced tillage, cover cropping, intercropping, diversified crop rotations, rotational grazing, composting, and mulching. The goal of regenerative agriculture is to build up and diversify soil organic matter, thereby promoting soil health, and mitigate climate change through the sequestering of carbon.

    As we highlight impacts, we should also call attention to organizations that are leading the way in improving soils. Their efforts include bringing scientists and policymakers together to address soil loss and soil biodiversity, as well as using storytelling and other forms of creative communication to raise consumer awareness about the connections between soil health, food security, and the climate.

    To maximize the potential of regenerative agriculture practices, more data-based evidence is desperately needed, including to show pathways for scaling. More than ever, scientists must work together with growers to address questions and remove obstacles preventing more people from adopting such practices.

    To maximize the potential of regenerative agriculture practices, more data-based evidence is desperately needed, including to show pathways for scaling. More than ever, scientists must work together with growers to address questions and remove obstacles preventing more people from adopting such practices.

    Which of the following is the closest in the meaning of ‘UNDERPINS’ as used in the passage?

    Revert

    Rapport

    Supports

    Report

    All are synonyms

    Directions: Read the following passage and answer the questions.

    On December 5, the world marked World Soil Day. The theme this year, “Stop Soil Erosion, Save our Future,” was chosen to raise awareness of the damage being done to soils around the world and start the process of reversing this trend.

    There is no doubt that they should. The importance of soil to human civilization cannot be overestimated – it is present in everything we touch. Healthy soil underpins agriculture, farm productivity, and national economies. It grows healthy food, reduces nutrient losses to waterways, reduces greenhouse-gas emissions, increases carbon sequestration, and strengthens biodiversity, all while enabling crops to cope with the changing climate. As such, the soil should be viewed as a natural, national, and strategic asset that must be managed wisely.

    Yet around the world, soils are being eroded, dried out, and degraded, owing to poor land use and intensive agricultural practices that deplete soil nutrients. Other factors contributing to poor soil health and erosion include deforestation, excessive use of nitrogen fertilizers, and overgrazing. Ultimately, these practices literally mine the life out of soils. It is time to reverse this damaging trend.

    One way to ensure that national governments and citizens appreciate soils and the value they hold is to put an economic price tag on them. Compelling recent evidence suggests that there are substantial profits to be made from caring about soils. Putting a price tag on the soil is the right way to encourage the necessary efforts.

    Regenerative agriculture, while encompassing many other principles, comprises sustainable farming practices such as reduced tillage, cover cropping, intercropping, diversified crop rotations, rotational grazing, composting, and mulching. The goal of regenerative agriculture is to build up and diversify soil organic matter, thereby promoting soil health, and mitigate climate change through the sequestering of carbon.

    As we highlight impacts, we should also call attention to organizations that are leading the way in improving soils. Their efforts include bringing scientists and policymakers together to address soil loss and soil biodiversity, as well as using storytelling and other forms of creative communication to raise consumer awareness about the connections between soil health, food security, and the climate.

    To maximize the potential of regenerative agriculture practices, more data-based evidence is desperately needed, including to show pathways for scaling. More than ever, scientists must work together with growers to address questions and remove obstacles preventing more people from adopting such practices.

    There are three food outlets (A, B, and C) which provide two types of food i.e. burger (veg + non-veg) and pizza (veg + non-veg). The caselet gives the information about the sale of burger and pizzas by three outlets on Monday. The number of non-veg burgers sold by outlet A on Monday is thrice the number of veg burgers sold on the same day. The total number of pizzas sold by outlet A is 140. The number of veg burgers sold by B on Monday is 20 less than the non-veg burgers sold by the same outlet on the same day. The number of veg pizzas sold by outlet A on Monday is half the number of veg burgers sold by outlet A on Monday. The total number of burgers and pizzas sold by C is 200 and 160 respectively. The ratio of the number of veg pizza sold to non-veg pizzas sold by outlet C is 1:3 respectively. The number of non-veg pizzas sold by C is same as the number of veg burgers sold by A. The number of veg-pizzas to non-veg pizzas sold by B is 4:5 respectively. Total number of burgers and pizzas together sold by B is 314. Number of non-veg burgers sold by B is 95 which is 5 less than the number of non-veg burgers sold by outlet C.

    The question consists of two statements numbered “I and II” given below it. You have to decide whether the data provided in the statements are sufficient to answer the question.

    Statement-I: Mr. Rao is 50% more efficient than Kalyani, and Chandrasekhar is 40% less efficient than Mr. Rao. The time taken by Chandrasekhar to complete the work is 2 days more than the time taken by Kalyani to complete the work.

    Statement-II: Kalyani and Mr. Rao can complete the work in 7.2 days.

    इस प्रश्न में दो कथन I और II दिए गए हैं|आपको यह तय करना है कि कथन में दी गई जानकारी उत्तर देने के लिए पर्याप्त है या नहीं|

    कार्य को समाप्त करने में Kalyani को कितना समय लगेगा?

    Statement-I: Mr. Rao Kalyani से 50% अधिक कार्यकुशल है और Chandrasekhar Mr Rao से 40% कम कार्यकुशल है|कार्य को समाप्त करने में Chandrasekhar द्वारा लिया गया समय कार्य को समाप्त करने में Kalyani द्वारा लिया गया समय से 2 days अधिक है|

    Statement-II: Kalyani और Mr. Rao कार्य को 7.2 days में समाप्त कर सकते हैं|

    The data in statement I alone are sufficient to answer the question, while the data in statement II alone are not sufficient to answer the question.

    सिर्फ कथन I में दी गयी जानकारी प्रश्न का उत्तर देने के लिए पर्याप्त है, जबकि सिर्फ कथन II में दी गई जानकारी उत्तर देने के लिए पर्याप्त नहीं है|

    The data in both statements I and II together are necessary to answer the question.

    The question consists of two statements numbered “I and II” given below it. You have to decide whether the data provided in the statements are sufficient to answer the question.

    The age of three friends A, B and C is (x – 4) years, (x + 4) years, and (x + 8) years respectively. Find the age of B.

    Statement-I: The average of age of A and C is (x – 16) years less than the average of age of B and C.

    Statement-II: The average of age of A and B is 6 years less than the average of age of B and C.

    इस प्रश्न में दो कथन I और II दिए गए हैं|आपको यह तय करना है कि कथन में दी गई जानकारी उत्तर देने के लिए पर्याप्त है या नहीं|

    तीन मित्र A, B और C की आयु क्रमशः (x – 4) वर्ष, (x + 4) वर्ष और (x + 8) वर्ष है|B की आयु ज्ञात करें|

    Statement-II: A और B की आयु का औसत, B और C की आयु के औसत से 6 वर्ष कम है|

    The question consists of two statements numbered “I and II” given below it. You have to decide whether the data provided in the statements are sufficient to answer the question.

    What is the time taken by Sumit to reach office from home, if the distance between his home and office is 120 km?

    Statement-I: If Sumit travels with a speed of (x – 1) km/hour, he reaches the office from home on time.

    Statement-II: If he travels at speed of (x - 4) km/hour, he is late by two hours.

    इस प्रश्न में दो कथन I और II दिए गए हैं|आपको यह तय करना है कि कथन में दी गई जानकारी उत्तर देने के लिए पर्याप्त है या नहीं|

    घर से कार्यालय पहुँचने में Sumit को कितना समय लगता है यदि उसके घर और कार्यालय के बीच की दुरी 120km है?

    Statement-I: यदि Sumit (x-1) km/hour की गति से यात्रा करता है, वह घर से कार्यालय समय पर पहुँचता है|

    Statement-II: यदि वह (x-4) km/hour की गति से यात्रा करता है, तो वह दो hours की देरी से पहुँचता है|

    The data in statement I alone are sufficient to answer the question, while the data in statement II alone are not sufficient to answer the question.

    सिर्फ कथन I में दी गयी जानकारी प्रश्न का उत्तर देने के लिए पर्याप्त है, जबकि सिर्फ कथन II में दी गई जानकारी उत्तर देने के लिए पर्याप्त नहीं है|

    The data given in both statements I and II together are not sufficient to answer the question.

    The data in both statements I and II together are necessary to answer the question.

    दोनों कथन I और II में दी गई संयुक्त जानकारी उत्तर देने के लिए जरुरी है|

    In the question, two quantities I and II are given. You have to solve both the quantities to establish the correct relation between Quantity-I and Quantity-II and choose the correct option.

    Quantity I: Atul and Arun together can complete a work in 24 days, while Ajit and Arun can complete the same work in 20 days. If the efficiency of Arun and Ajit is same, then in how many days can Atul alone complete 50% of the work?

    Quantity II: P and Q alone can complete the work in 40 days and 60 days respectively. Find the time taken by both of them working together to complete the work.

    निम्नलिखित प्रश्न में, दो मात्राएँ I और II दिए गए हैं|आपको दोनों मात्राओं को हल कर मात्रा-I और मात्रा-II के बीच सही सम्बन्ध को स्थापित कर सही विकल्प का चुनाव करना है|

    मात्रा I: Atul और Arun एक साथ 24 दिनों में एक काम पूरा कर सकते हैं, जबकि Ajit और Arun इसी कम को 20 दिनों में पूरा कर सकते हैं। अगर Arun और Ajit की कार्यक्षमता समान है, तो 50% काम को अकेले Atul कितने दिनों में को पूरा कर सकता है?

    मात्रा II: P और Q अकेले क्रमशः 40 दिनों और 60 दिनों में काम पूरा कर सकते हैं।कार्य को दोनों साथ में कितने समय में पूरा करते हैं?

    Quantity-I > Quantity-II

    मात्रा-I > मात्रा-II

    Quantity-I < Quantity-II

    मात्रा-I < मात्रा-II

    Quantity-I ≤ Quantity-II

    मात्रा-I ≤ मात्रा-II

    Quantity-I = Quantity-II or No relation

    मात्रा-II और कोई सम्बन्ध नहीं

    Quantity-I ≥ Quantity-II

    मात्रा-I ≥ मात्रा-II

    In the question, two quantities I and II are given. You have to solve both the quantities to establish the correct relation between Quantity-I and Quantity-II and choose the correct option.

    Quantity-I: 600 ml of mixture (milk + water) contains 60% of water in it. Find the quantity of milk that must be added into the mixture so that quantity of water in the resultant mixture becomes 37.5%.

    Quantity-II: 300 ml.

    प्रश्न में, दो मात्राएँ I और II दी गई हैं। आपको मात्रा- I और मात्रा- II के बीच सही संबंध स्थापित करने के लिए दोनों संबंधों को हल करना है और सही विकल्प चुनना है।

    मात्रा- I: 600 ml मिश्रण (दूध + पानी) में 60% पानी होता है। दूध की मात्रा ज्ञात कीजिए जिसे मिश्रण में मिलाया जाना चाहिए ताकि परिणामी मिश्रण में पानी की मात्रा 37.5% हो जाए।

    मात्रा- II: 300 ml

    Quantity-I > Quantity-II

    मात्रा- I> मात्रा- II

    Quantity-I < Quantity-II

    मात्रा- I< मात्रा- II

    Quantity-I ≤ Quantity-II

    मात्रा- I≤ मात्रा- II

    Quantity-I = Quantity-II or No relation

    मात्रा- I = मात्रा- II या कोई संबंध नहीं

    Quantity-I ≥ Quantity-II

    मात्रा- I≥ मात्रा- II

    General Instructions:

    1. The clock will be set at the server. The countdown timer in the top right corner of screen will display the remaining time available for you to complete the examination. When the timer reaches zero, the examination will end by itself. You will not be required to end or submit your examination.
    2. The Question Palette displayed on the right side of screen will show the status of each question using one of the following symbols:
      1 You have not visited the question yet.
      3 You have not answered the question.
      5 You have answered the question.
      7 You have NOT answered the question, but have marked the question for review.
      9 You have answered the question, but marked it for review.
      The Marked for Review status for a question simply indicates that you would like to look at that question again. If a question is answered and Marked for Review, your answer for that question will be considered in the evaluation.
    3. You can click on the ">" arrow which appears to the left of question palette to collapse the question palette thereby maximizing the question window. To view the question palette again, you can click on "<" which appears on the right side of question window.

    Navigating to a Question :

    1. To answer a question, do the following:
      1. Click on the question number in the Question Palette at the right of your screen to go to that numbered question directly. Note that using this option does NOT save your answer to the current question.
      2. To deselect your chosen answer, click on the button of the chosen option again or click on the Clear Response button
      3. To change your chosen answer, click on the button of another option
      4. To save your answer, you MUST click on the Save & Next button
      5. To mark the question for review, click on the Mark for Review & Next button.If an answer is selected for a question that is Marked for Review, that answer will be considered in the evaluation.

    Answering a Question :

    1. Procedure for answering a multiple choice type question:
      1. To select your answer, click on the button of one of the options
      2. To deselect your chosen answer, click on the button of the chosen option again or click on the
      3. To change your chosen answer, click on the button of another option
      4. To save your answer, you MUST click on the Save & Next button
      5. To mark the question for review, click on the Mark for Review & Next button.If an answer is selected for a question that is Marked for Review, that answer will be considered in the evaluation.
    2. To change your answer to a question that has already been answered, first select that question for answering and then follow the procedure for answering that type of question.
    3. Note that ONLY Questions for which answers are saved or marked for review after answering will be considered for evaluation.

    Navigating through sections:

    1. Sections in this question paper are displayed on the top bar of the screen. Questions in a section can be viewed by clicking on the section name. The section you are currently viewing is highlighted.
    2. After clicking the Save & Next button on the last question for a section, you will automatically be taken to the first question of the next section.
    3. You can shuffle between tests and questions anytime during the examination as per your convenience only during the time stipulated.
    4. Candidate can view the corresponding section summary as part of the legend that appears in every section above the question palette.

    All the best!

    Directions: Answer the questions based on the information given below.

    The bar graph given below shows the number of Indian families and percentage of families who are Tibetans with respect to the total number of families visiting that monastery in Himachal Pradesh on Sunday.

    Note: Number of families visiting any monastery = Number of Indian families + Number of Tibetan families visiting that monastery.

    दिशानिर्देश: नीचे दी गई जानकारी के आधार पर प्रश्नों का उत्तर दें।

    नीचे दिया गया बार ग्राफ़ Sunday को Himachal Pradesh में उस मठ का दौरा करने वाले परिवारों की कुल संख्या के संबंध में भारतीय परिवारों की संख्या और Tibetan परिवारों की प्रतिशत दिखाता है।

    नोट: किसी भी मठ पर जाने वाले परिवारों की संख्या = उस मठ पर जाने वाले भारतीय परिवारों की संख्या + उस मठ पर जाने वाले Tibetan परिवारों की संख्या।

    1

    If n = Total number of families visiting Tashi Jong monastery on Sunday – Total number of families visiting Key monastery on Sunday, then find the value of √(n + 82 – 19).

    यदि n = Sunday को Tashi Jong monastery का दौरा करने वाले परिवारों की कुल संख्या - Sunday को Key monastery पर जाने वाले परिवारों की कुल संख्या है, तो √(n + 82 – 19) का मान बताइए ?

    2

    What is the ratio of the number of Indian families visiting Kungri Monastery on Sunday to the number of Tibetan families visiting Tashi Jong Monastery on Sunday?

    Sunday को Kungri Monastery यात्रा करने वाले भारतीय परिवारों की संख्या और Sunday को Tashi Jong Monastery का दौरा करने वाले Tibetan परिवारों की संख्या का अनुपात क्या होगा?

    3

    On an average, there are 5 members per Indian family and 6 members per Tibetan family. Find the total number of persons visiting Kardang Monastery on Sunday.

    औसतन, प्रत्येक भारतीय परिवार में 5 सदस्य और प्रत्येक Tibetan परिवार में 6 सदस्य हैं। Sunday को Kardang Monastery पर जाने वाले लोगों की कुल संख्या बताइए ?

    4

    Quantity I: x = Total number of families visiting Tashi Jong Monastery on Sunday – Number of Indian families visiting Kardang Monastery on Sunday. Find the value of x.

    Quantity II: y = Number of Indian families visiting Tayul Monastery on Sunday + Number of Tibetan families visiting Key Monastery on Sunday. Find the value of y.

    मात्रा I: x = Sunday को Tashi Jong Monastery यात्रा करने वाले परिवारों की कुल संख्या - Sunday को Kardang Monastery का यात्रा करने वाले भारतीय परिवारों की संख्या, x का मान ज्ञात करें।

    मात्रा II: y = Sunday को Tayul Monastery का दौरा करने वाले भारतीय परिवारों की संख्या + Sunday को Key Monastery का दौरा करने वाले Tibetan परिवारों की संख्या। y का मान ज्ञात करें।

    5

    Number of Indian families and number of Tibetan families visiting Kardang monastery on Monday are 20% and 10% less than the number of Indian families and Tibetan families visiting Kardang monastery on Sunday, respectively. Find the total number of families visiting Kardang monastery on Monday.

    Monday को Kardang monastery का दौरा करने वाले भारतीय परिवारों और तिब्बती परिवारों की संख्या Sunday को Kardang monastery का दौरा करने वाले भारतीय परिवारों और तिब्बती परिवारों की संख्या से क्रमशः 20% और 10% कम है। Monday को Kardang monastery पर जाने वाले परिवारों की कुल संख्या ज्ञात करें।

    6

    In the question below there are three statements followed by two conclusions I and II. You have to take the three given statements to be true even if they seem to be at variance from commonly known facts and then decide which of the given conclusions logically follows from the three statements disregarding commonly known facts.

    Statements:

    No line is circle

    Only a few circle is square

    All square is graph

    Conclusions:

    I. All circle is graph

    II. Some square are not line

    प्रश्न में तीन कथन और उसके बाद दो निष्कर्ष I और II दिए गए हैं। आपको दिए गए तीन कथनों को सत्य मानना है, भले ही वे सामान्य रूप से ज्ञात तथ्यों से अलग दिखाई देते हों और फिर तय करें कि दिए गए निष्कर्षों में से कौन-सा निष्कर्ष सामान्य रूप से ज्ञात तथ्यों की अवहेलना करते हुए तीन कथनों का तार्किक रूप से अनुसरण करता है।

    कथन:

    कोई line circle नहीं है।

    केवल कुछ circle square है।

    सभी square graph है।

    निष्कर्ष:

    I. सभी circle graph है।

    II. कुछ square line नहीं है।
    7

    In the question below there are three statements followed by two conclusions I and II. You have to take the three given statements to be true even if they seem to be at variance from commonly known facts and then decide which of the given conclusions logically follows from the three statements disregarding commonly known facts.

    Statements:

    Only a few Feb is Jan

    All Jan is April

    Only April is Jun

    Conclusions:

    I. All Jan being Feb is a possibility

    II. Some Jun can be Jan

    प्रश्न में तीन कथन और उसके बाद दो निष्कर्ष I और II दिए गए हैं। आपको दिए गए तीन कथनों को सत्य मानना है, भले ही वे सामान्य रूप से ज्ञात तथ्यों से अलग दिखाई देते हों और फिर तय करें कि दिए गए निष्कर्षों में से कौन-सा निष्कर्ष सामान्य रूप से ज्ञात तथ्यों की अवहेलना करते हुए तीन कथनों का तार्किक रूप से अनुसरण करता है।

    कथन:

    केवल कुछ Feb Jan है।

    सभी Jan April है।

    केवल April Jun है।

    निष्कर्ष:

    I. सभी Jan के Feb होने की संभावना है।

    II. कुछ Jun Jan हो सकते हैं।

    In the question below there are three statements followed by two conclusions I and II. You have to take the three given statements to be true even if they seem to be at variance from commonly known facts and then decide which of the given conclusions logically follows from the three statements disregarding commonly known facts.

    Statements:

    Only a few wood is bench

    No table is chair

    All chair is bench

    Conclusions:

    I. Few bench is table

    II. Some chair being wood is a possibility

    प्रश्न में तीन कथन और उसके बाद दो निष्कर्ष I और II दिए गए हैं। आपको दिए गए तीन कथनों को सत्य मानना है, भले ही वे सामान्य रूप से ज्ञात तथ्यों से अलग दिखाई देते हों और फिर तय करें कि दिए गए निष्कर्षों में से कौन-सा निष्कर्ष सामान्य रूप से ज्ञात तथ्यों की अवहेलना करते हुए तीन कथनों का तार्किक रूप से अनुसरण करता है।

    कथन:

    केवल कुछ wood bench है।

    कोई table chair नहीं है।

    सभी chair bench है।

    निष्कर्ष:

    I. कुछ bench table है।

    II. कुछ chair के wood होने की संभावना है।

    Directions: Answer the questions based on the information given below.

    Six persons A, B, C, D, E and F have different weights. A is heavier than two persons. C is heavier than at least two persons. F is heavier than B, who is heavier than A. Number of persons heavier than B is equal to number of persons lighter than D.

    निर्देश: नीचे दी गई जानकारी के आधार पर प्रश्नों के उत्तर दें।

    छह व्यक्तियों A, B, C, D, E और F का भार अलग-अलग हैं। A दो व्यक्तियों से भारी है। C कम से कम दो व्यक्तियों से भारी है। F B से भारी है और B A से भारी है। B से भारी व्यक्तियों की संख्या D से हल्के व्यक्तियों की संख्या के बराबर है।

    Directions: Answer the questions based on the information given below.

    There are two types of flats X and Y on each floor of a building.The bottommost floor is numbered as 1 and the topmost floor is numbered 5. Flat X is in west of flat Y. One person lives on each floor of each flat. There are five floors.

    Note: If a person lives n number of floors above/below another person then both must live in same type of flat until and unless stated otherwise. Also, person living on a floor of flat X is in west of person living on the same floor of flat Y.

    E lives two floors above H.F lives below G in the same type of flat but not immediately below G.B lives below F but not in the same type of flat.C lives immediately above J.A doesn’t live in flat Y.G lives in the north-west of E.F and D live on the same floor. I and A also live in the building.

    निर्देश: नीचे दी गई जानकारी के आधार पर प्रश्नों के उत्तर दें।

    एक इमारत के प्रत्येक मंजिल पर दो प्रकार के फ्लैट X और Y हैं। सबसे निचली मंजिल की संख्या 1 है और सबसे ऊपरी मंजिल की संख्या 5 है। फ्लैट X फ्लैट Y के पश्चिम में है। प्रत्येक मंजिल की प्रत्येक फ्लैट में एक व्यक्ति रहता है। पांच मंजिल हैं।

    ध्यान दें : यदि कोई व्यक्ति किसी अन्य व्यक्ति के n संख्या में ऊपर/नीचे वाली मंजिलों पर रहता है तो दोनों को एक ही प्रकार के फ्लैट में रहना चाहिए अन्यथा जब तक कुछ और ना कहा जाए। साथ ही, एक मंजिल पर फ्लैट X में रहने वाला व्यक्ति, समान मंजिल पर फ्लैट Y में रहने वाले व्यक्ति के पश्चिम में है।

    E H से दो मंजिल ऊपर रहता है| F G के नीचे एक ही प्रकार के फ्लैट में रहता है लेकिन G के तत्काल नीचे नहीं रहता है| B F के नीचे रहता है लेकिन समान प्रकार के फ्लैट में नहीं रहता है। C J के तत्काल ऊपर रहता है| A फ्लैट Y में नहीं रहता है। G E के उत्तर-पश्चिम में रहता है। F और D एक ही मंजिल पर रहते हैं। I और A भी इमारत में रहते हैं।

    Directions: Answer the questions based on the information given below.

    A person starts walking in south direction from point M, after walking 4m he turns left from point N and the walks for 3m till point O. He then turns left from point O and walks for 6m till point P and then turns right and walks for 4m till point Q and then turns right and walks for 9m till point R. He then turns right and walks for 4m and then turns left from point S and walks for 3m till point T.

    निर्देश: नीचे दी गई जानकारी के आधार पर प्रश्नों के उत्तर दें।

    एक व्यक्ति बिंदु M से दक्षिण दिशा में चलना शुरू करता है, 4m चलने के बाद वह बिंदु N से बाएं मुड़ता है और बिंदु O तक 3m चलता है। फिर वह बिंदु O से बाएं मुड़ता है और बिंदु P तक 6m चलता है और फिर दाएं मुड़ता है और बिंदु Q तक 4m चलता है और फिर दाएं मुड़ता है और बिंदु R तक 9m चलता है। फिर वह दाएं मुड़ता है और 4m चलता है और फिर बिंदु S से बाएं मुड़ता है और बिंदु T तक 3m चलता है।

    34

    बिंदु S के सन्दर्भ में बिंदु M किस दिशा में है?

    What is the shortest distance between T and R?

    Directions: Answer the questions based on the information given below.

    Six functions A, B, C, D, E and F are held on 1st of different months (March, April, May, July, August and September) in the same year. These functions are held in different places among Bhopal, Pune, Jaipur, Chennai, Mumbai and Hyderabad.

    Two functions are held between F and D, which is held in a month, which has only 30 days.One function is held between C and the one held in Mumbai. E is held in Chennai but after C.

    Function in Pune is held before A.Function in Bhopal is held four months after B. The function in Mumbai is held immediately before F. Function in Hyderabad is not held in a month, which has only 30 days.

    निर्देश: नीचे दी गई जानकारी के आधार पर प्रश्नों के उत्तर दें।

    छह समारोह A, B, C, D, E और F एक ही वर्ष में अलग-अलग महीनों (मार्च, अप्रैल, मई, जुलाई, अगस्त और सितंबर) की पहली तारीख को आयोजित किए जाते हैं। ये समारोह भोपाल, पुणे, जयपुर, चेन्नई, मुंबई और हैदराबाद के बीच विभिन्न स्थानों पर आयोजित किए जाते हैं।

    F और D के बीच दो समारोह आयोजित किए जाते हैं और D को उस महीने में आयोजित किया जाता है, जिसमें केवल 30 दिन होते हैं। C और मुंबई में आयोजित एक समारोह के बीच एक समारोह आयोजित किया जाता है। E चेन्नई में आयोजित किया जाता है लेकिन C के बाद।

    पुणे में समारोह को A से पहले आयोजित किया जाता है। भोपाल में समारोह को B के चार महीने बाद आयोजित किया जाता है। मुंबई में समारोह को F से ठीक पहले आयोजित किया जाता है। हैदराबाद में समारोह उस महीने में नहीं होता है, जिसमें केवल 30 दिन होते हैं।

    Directions: Read the following passage carefully and answer the questions.

    Many of the important benefits of a plant-based diet – particularly for climate health and animals – are well known. Yet despite the science being very clear, there remains confusion about the impact on human health. We have long known for example, that a diet centred around whole plant-foods – fruits, vegetables, whole-grains, beans, nuts and seeds – significantly reduces the risk of heart disease, type 2 diabetes, obesity and certain cancers. In fact, a low fat plant-based diet is the only diet to have been shown to actually reverse established coronary artery disease. It has also been seen to reverse type 2 diabetes, enable effective and sustained weight loss without portion control or exercise, and arrest the progression of early stage prostate cancer.

    Diet choices can have a major impact on mood and mental health, and there is a very good reason for this. Diet affects the health of our gut bacteria, which produce many of the hormones active in the brain. Gut bacteria thrive on fibre, which is only found in whole plant foods. So it is no surprise to find that a plant-based diet can benefit mental health. In a study, participants who were overweight or had a history of type 2 diabetes were either prescribed a low-fat vegan diet or asked to continue their usual diet for 18 weeks. The results showed a significant improvement in mental health, wellbeing and work productivity in those on the vegan diet, as well as lower levels of depression and anxiety.

    Osteoarthritis, the painful breakdown of cartilage in the joints, appears to be an inevitable consequence of ageing. It is not reversible but it is manageable, usually with pain medication and sometimes surgery.

    So what role could a plant-based diet play here? One small study looking at the diet’s impact showed a significant improvement in self-reported pain and functioning in people with osteoarthritis. One reason for this could be the anti-inflammatory properties of the micro-nutrients present in plant foods, as inflammation is the main cause of pain in arthritis. Meat-based diets have the opposite effect and, in general, increase the level of inflammation in the body.

    Urinary tract infections (UTIs) are one of the most common causes of infection in the general population with the bacteria Escherichia coli (E coli) often being the culprit. Infection can occur because E coli from the intestine finds its way into the urinary tract. But UTIs can also be caused by E coli strains commonly found in farm animals such as chickens and pigs, so eating contaminated sources of meat can lead to infection. Given the link between E coli and UTIs, It might seem obvious that those on a plant-based diet who avoid meat might have a lower risk of infection, but whether this was the case was not known for sure until recent research came out. The analysis of several studies shows that vegetarians have a 16% lower risk of UTIs compared to non-vegetarians. This confirms previous data suggesting that meat-borne bacteria are a major contributor to the risk of UTIs. Increasingly these food borne bacteria are displaying antibiotic resistance.

    So if those following a health plant-based diet have a lower risk of ill health then surely this will save on health costs. In a large Taiwanese study, vegetarians were found to have a lower rate of outpatient visits, which translated into a 13% lower outpatient expenditure and a 15% lower total medical expenditure. So it is interesting to hypothesise the health economic impact of a plant-based diet on the UK’s cash-strapped National Health Service. In 2017, spending on healthcare in the UK totalled £197 billion – approximately £2,989 per person. If everyone in the country shifted to a vegetarian diet, this could (using the 15% reduction as a guide) reduce healthcare expenditure by £30 billion. Plant-based diets then, not only have the potential to dramatically improve human and planetary health, but could have significant benefits for the health of the economy too.

    Directions: Read the following passage carefully and answer the questions.

    Many of the important benefits of a plant-based diet - particularly for climate health and animals - are well known. Yet despite the science being very clear, there remains confusion about the impact on human health. We have long known for example, that a diet centred around whole plant-foods - fruits, vegetables, whole-grains, beans, nuts and seeds - significantly reduces the risk of heart disease, type 2 diabetes, obesity and certain cancers. In fact, a low fat plant-based diet is the only diet to have been shown to actually reverse established coronary artery disease. It has also been seen to reverse type 2 diabetes, enable effective and sustained weight loss without portion control or exercise, and arrest the progression of early stage prostate cancer.

    Diet choices can have a major impact on mood and mental health, and there is a very good reason for this. Diet affects the health of our gut bacteria, which produce many of the hormones active in the brain. Gut bacteria thrive on fibre, which is only found in whole plant foods. So it is no surprise to find that a plant-based diet can benefit mental health. In a study, participants who were overweight or had a history of type 2 diabetes were either prescribed a low-fat vegan diet or asked to continue their usual diet for 18 weeks. The results showed a significant improvement in mental health, wellbeing and work productivity in those on the vegan diet, as well as lower levels of depression and anxiety.

    Osteoarthritis, the painful breakdown of cartilage in the joints, appears to be an inevitable consequence of ageing. It is not reversible but it is manageable, usually with pain medication and sometimes surgery.

    Directions: Read the following passage and answer the questions.

    On December 5, the world marked World Soil Day. The theme this year, “Stop Soil Erosion, Save our Future,” was chosen to raise awareness of the damage being done to soils around the world and start the process of reversing this trend.

    There is no doubt that they should. The importance of soil to human civilization cannot be overestimated – it is present in everything we touch. Healthy soil underpins agriculture, farm productivity, and national economies. It grows healthy food, reduces nutrient losses to waterways, reduces greenhouse-gas emissions, increases carbon sequestration, and strengthens biodiversity, all while enabling crops to cope with the changing climate. As such, the soil should be viewed as a natural, national, and strategic asset that must be managed wisely.

    Yet around the world, soils are being eroded, dried out, and degraded, owing to poor land use and intensive agricultural practices that deplete soil nutrients. Other factors contributing to poor soil health and erosion include deforestation, excessive use of nitrogen fertilizers, and overgrazing. Ultimately, these practices literally mine the life out of soils. It is time to reverse this damaging trend.

    One way to ensure that national governments and citizens appreciate soils and the value they hold is to put an economic price tag on them. Compelling recent evidence suggests that there are substantial profits to be made from caring about soils. Putting a price tag on the soil is the right way to encourage the necessary efforts.

    Regenerative agriculture, while encompassing many other principles, comprises sustainable farming practices such as reduced tillage, cover cropping, intercropping, diversified crop rotations, rotational grazing, composting, and mulching. The goal of regenerative agriculture is to build up and diversify soil organic matter, thereby promoting soil health, and mitigate climate change through the sequestering of carbon.

    As we highlight impacts, we should also call attention to organizations that are leading the way in improving soils. Their efforts include bringing scientists and policymakers together to address soil loss and soil biodiversity, as well as using storytelling and other forms of creative communication to raise consumer awareness about the connections between soil health, food security, and the climate.

    To maximize the potential of regenerative agriculture practices, more data-based evidence is desperately needed, including to show pathways for scaling. More than ever, scientists must work together with growers to address questions and remove obstacles preventing more people from adopting such practices.

    Monthly income of Kunal is 82% more than the monthly savings of Kunal. If the total monthly expenditure of Kunal is Rs. 49200 and Kunal spends 15% of his monthly income in house rent, then find the monthly house rent paid by Kunal.

    Kunal की मासिक आय Kunal की मासिक बचत से 82% अधिक है। यदि Kunal का कुल मासिक व्यय Rs. 49200 और Kunal ने अपनी मासिक आय का 15% घर के किराए पर खर्च किया, फिर Kunal द्वारा भुगतान किया गया मासिक घर किराया ज्ञात करे ?

    118

    Present age of Komal is 16 years more than the present age of Neha. After 6 years, ratio of age of Komal to age of Neha will become 5:3. If Pankaj is 12 years older than Neha, then find the ratio of present age of Pankaj to present age of Neha.

    Komal की वर्तमान आयु Neha की वर्तमान आयु से 16 वर्ष अधिक है। 6 वर्षों के बाद, Komal की आयु और Neha की आयु का अनुपात क्रमशः 5: 3 हो जाएगा। यदि Pankaj, Neha से 12 वर्ष बड़ा है, तो Pankaj की वर्तमान आयु और Neha की वर्तमान आयु का अनुपात ज्ञात करें|

    Pawan reaches his office from his home on time with his actual speed. One day, he was 10 minutes late for his office and thus increases his speed by 10 km/h and reaches office on time. If his actual speed is 30 km/h, then at what time his office starts provided normally he leaves home at 8:50 AM?

    Pawan अपने घर से वास्तविक गति से 10 minutes पहले अपने कार्यालय पहुंचा । एक दिन, वह अपने कार्यालय के लिए 10 minutes देरी से था और इस लिए वह अपनी गति को 10 km/h से बढ़ाता है और समय पर कार्यालय पहुंच जाता है। यदि उसकी वास्तविक गति 30 km/h है, तो अगर वह 8:50 AM पर घर छोड़ देता है सामान्य रूप से उसके कार्यालय के शुरू होने का समय क्या होगा?

The number of postpaid SIM cards of Airtel sold by shopkeeper is 48.

    Quantity-II: 300 ml.

    प्रश्न में, दो मात्राएँ I और II दी गई हैं। आपको मात्रा- I और मात्रा- II के बीच सही संबंध स्थापित करने के लिए दोनों संबंधों को हल करना है और सही विकल्प चुनना है।

    मात्रा- I: 600 ml मिश्रण (दूध + पानी) में 60% पानी होता है। दूध की मात्रा ज्ञात कीजिए जिसे मिश्रण में मिलाया जाना चाहिए ताकि परिणामी मिश्रण में पानी की मात्रा 37.5% हो जाए।
